          <div class="faq-num">07</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m considering selling my independent practice. Should I close on a mortgage before or after the sale?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Depends on the structure. Pre-sale closing qualifies on established S-corp K-1 history (predictable, well-documented). Post-sale closing qualifies on the multi-source post-acquisition picture (ongoing W-2 + rollover K-1 + earnouts) which often supports larger qualifying. The trade-off: pre-sale provides immediate certainty; post-sale requires 12-18 months post-acquisition documentation for the new structure to season. We model both scenarios.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m an equine practitioner with mobile practice. How does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Equine and large-animal practitioners with mobile practice common run S-corp structures with significant business mileage and equipment depreciation. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.4-02/analyzing-returns-partnership-or-s-corporation" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.4-02</a>, we aggregate W-2 reasonable comp plus K-1 distributions plus Form 1084 addbacks for vehicle depreciation, mobile equipment (portable ultrasound, digital radiography, dental equipment), and other non-cash deductions. Mobile equine practice income runs $150K-$250K typically.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What documentation do I need for a veterinarian mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Typically: two years of complete federal 1040s with all schedules including Schedule C if applicable; if practice owner, Form 1120-S returns with K-1s and Schedule L; all W-2s including production bonus; any 1099-NECs from relief work, emergency hospital, or consulting; current servicer statement showing actual IDR payment; 60 days of personal bank statements; DVM degree documentation; NAVLE licensure verification; state veterinary license; AVMA specialty diplomate certification if applicable; USDA accreditation if doing federal work; PE sale documentation if post-sale.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My ACVECC emergency/critical care specialty W-2 is much higher than the BLS median. Does that count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; ACVECC emergency and critical care specialty diplomates at specialty referral hospitals commonly run $180K-$280K, substantially above the $130K BLS median. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, the specialty premium W-2 plus case-load production qualifies as variable income with 24-month average. We document the ACVECC diplomate certification and emergency hospital W-2 history.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are mortgage rates higher for veterinarians?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Base conventional and jumbo rates are the same for veterinarians as for any other borrower at the same credit profile. Veterinarians don&rsquo;t receive Physician Loan rate concessions because they&rsquo;re typically not eligible for Physician Loan products. However, Conventional Conforming and Jumbo at standard rates with proper B3-6-05 IDR documentation produce strong outcomes &mdash; we work within that framework efficiently.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I work at a USDA APHIS regulatory veterinary role. Does PSLF affect my mortgage planning?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Indirectly but favorably. USDA APHIS, FDA Center for Veterinary Medicine, military veterinary corps, Indian Health Service, and state public health agency veterinarians qualify for <a href="https://studentaid.gov/manage-loans/forgiveness-cancellation/public-service" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PSLF</a>. Your IDR payments count toward forgiveness AND count in DTI under B3-6-05. For veterinarians with $200K-$400K DVM loans, the 10-year PSLF clock plus IDR substantially reduces the long-term effective loan burden.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My spouse is also a veterinarian. How does that affect us?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Two-veterinarian households produce strong joint qualifying. Both files combine as co-borrowers with W-2s, production pay, K-1 distributions if practice partners, and IDR payments. Two-DVM households both with $200K-$400K of student loans on PAYE benefit substantially from B3-6-05 treatment vs the 1% rule. Combined households commonly qualify for $1M-$1.8M mortgages.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My S-corp practice has significant equipment depreciation. How does that work for qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Form 1084 cash-flow analysis recovers non-cash depreciation as addback under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/167" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 167</a> and Section 179 expensing for veterinary equipment (digital radiography, ultrasound, CT, MRI for advanced specialty practices, dental equipment, surgical equipment, laboratory analyzers). Veterinary practices commonly run $80K-$250K of equipment depreciation per year that Form 1084 restores to qualifying income.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I work at a veterinary pharmaceutical company (Zoetis). How does my RSU comp count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Veterinary pharmaceutical industry employment (Zoetis, Boehringer Ingelheim Animal Health, Merck Animal Health, Elanco) commonly includes W-2 base + cash bonus + RSU equity comp. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, base + bonus qualifies with 24-month average. RSU vesting qualifies with 24-month vesting history. Total industry vet comp runs $150K-$250K typically.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m considering acquiring an independent veterinary practice. How does SBA financing coordinate with personal mortgage?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Veterinary practice acquisitions typically run $400K-$2M depending on revenue and goodwill. <a href="https://www.sba.gov/funding-programs/loans/7a-loans" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SBA 7(a)</a> financing up to $5M is the norm for veterinary acquisitions. We sequence the personal mortgage either BEFORE the SBA closes (qualifying on employed-period W-2) or AFTER the acquired practice integrates 60-180 days post-acquisition with established K-1 history.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can a co-borrower help me qualify?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, significantly. Co-borrower files combine W-2s, 1099s, Schedule C, and S-corp distributions from both parties. For new-grad veterinarians in the first 1-2 years where W-2 income is still establishing and DVM debt is high, a co-borrower with stable W-2 income often substantially helps qualifying ratios. Common scenarios: spouse W-2 employment, partner W-2 employment, or parent co-signer.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My S-corp practice has retained earnings. Are those usable as reserves?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Generally yes if accessible. S-corp retained earnings in the practice business account count as reserves if you have the ability to distribute them. Documented via 1120-S Schedule L (balance sheet). For established practice owners with 5+ years of accumulated retained earnings, the reserve strength supports jumbo qualifying. Equipment investments are fixed assets, not liquid reserves &mdash; we separate the two on Schedule L analysis.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does the IRS Section 199A QBI deduction affect me as a veterinary practice owner?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Veterinary practice operating IS classified as Specified Service Trade or Business (SSTB) under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/businesses/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 199A</a> &mdash; veterinary medicine is health field SSTB similar to medicine and dentistry. SSTB phase-out applies at $191,950-$241,950 for single filers (2024 indexed) and $383,900-$483,900 for joint filers. Many practice owners sit ABOVE the phase-out and lose the QBI deduction entirely. We coordinate with your CPA on documentation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are there mortgage programs specifically designed for veterinarians?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">A small number of specialty lenders extend veterinarian-specific products with low-down structure similar to Physician Loan extension &mdash; these are less common than Physician Loan extension to NPs/PAs. The realistic answer: for most veterinarians, Conventional Conforming or Jumbo with proper B3-6-05 IDR documentation is the optimal path. What matters more is finding a broker who understands base + production pay variable income treatment, AVMA boarded specialty premium context, independent and post-PE-sale practice multi-source documentation, relief 1099 aggregation, and DVM IDR documentation for the substantial student loan burden.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m in a 3-year specialty residency at a teaching hospital. Can I qualify now or wait until I&rsquo;m boarded?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Specialty residency W-2 ($50K-$70K range, below regular new-grad veterinarian W-2) limits current qualifying capacity. Most veterinarians wait until completion of specialty residency (and ideally 6-12 months into the boarded specialty W-2) before pursuing larger jumbo purchases. Smaller starter homes may be feasible during specialty residency depending on co-borrower income and IDR documentation.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My production-based pay varies seasonally with case load. How does the underwriter treat that?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Seasonal variation is normal for veterinary production pay &mdash; flea/tick season, summer surgical volumes, holiday boarding, etc. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.1-01/general-income-information" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.1-01</a>, the 24-month average smooths seasonal variation. We document the production formula and the 2-year production history showing the underlying earning capacity even with monthly variability.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m a mixed-animal practitioner in a rural area. Does rural setting affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Rural veterinary practice doesn&rsquo;t fundamentally change qualifying mechanics &mdash; the same B3-3.1-01 (W-2) and B3-3.4-02 (S-corp practice ownership) rules apply. Rural mixed-animal practitioners may qualify for additional federal loan-repayment programs (Veterinary Medicine Loan Repayment Program through USDA NIFA) that reduce student loan burden &mdash; these federal programs work alongside IDR for B3-6-05 documentation purposes.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 90-120 days before you intend to make an offer. Veterinarian files benefit from runway because of base + production pay variable income documentation, possible AVMA boarded specialty diplomate documentation, relief 1099 supplementation aggregation, and (for practice owners) S-corp 1120-S review with Form 1084 addbacks for veterinary diagnostic imaging and surgical equipment. Post-PE-sale veterinarians may need additional documentation for the multi-source post-acquisition structure.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why do generalist lenders refuse veterinarian files when there&rsquo;s clearly stable income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Four reasons: (1) the $200K-$400K DVM debt with 1% rule treatment ($2,000-$4,000/month theoretical DTI hit) creates a DTI ratio that disqualifies the file before B3-6-05 IDR documentation rescues it; (2) production-based pay gets mis-categorized as &lsquo;commission/not stable&rsquo; rather than properly aggregated under B3-3.1-01 variable income with 24-month average; (3) post-PE-sale structures (rollover equity, multi-year earnouts) get refused entirely as &lsquo;non-standard&rsquo; rather than properly documented under B3-3.4-02; (4) some lenders waste time chasing Physician Loan eligibility for veterinarians before realizing it&rsquo;s not available. The income is all there and verifiable &mdash; the file just needs a broker who reads the veterinary multi-source structure correctly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

